{"id":"gekWvr9Y","lastModified":"2016-05-07T08:13:41.251Z","names":["Black Mustard Seeds","Mustard Seeds"],"description":"Refers to the black or brown mustard seeds usually found in Indian grocery stores. They are smaller and hotter than their yellow counterparts. 

Black mustard seeds are an essential ingredient for 'tempering' Indian dishes. 

Store them in a cool, dry place in your pantry and they will last for several months.","category":"Herbs and Spices","vegan":true}

ingredient:item.QBFdQgP0:
{"id":"QBFdQgP0","lastModified":"2016-05-07T08:10:03.32Z","names":["Carrot"],"description":"A root vegetable that can add colour and sweetness to almost any dish, sweet or savoury. They are generally washed and peeled before use. You can leave the peels on but it can make the carrot go dark and lose that lovely bright orange colour.

Eat them whole and raw or in salads, juice them, blend into soups, add to stews, curries, pies or casseroles, make cakes, the possibilities are endless.

Buy fresh and store in the refrigerator for about 2 weeks","category":"Vegetables and Fruits","vegan":true}

ingredient:item.slR9aCV6:
{"id":"slR9aCV6","lastModified":"2016-05-07T08:14:57.771Z","names":["Saffron"],"description":"This is possibly the most expensive spice in the world, but only a few strands are needed in most recipes. It is available as strands or in powdered form. It is best to buy the strands as they are less likely to be fake. Buy strands that are red with orange tips.

Saffron powder can be added directly to dishes, while the strands have to be soaked in hot water or milk first. 

They are available in most supermarkets, but you can get them for less in Middle-Eastern grocery stores. Buy in small quantities and store in an airtight container in your pantry. It will last for several months. ","category":"Herbs and Spices","vegan":true}

ingredient:item.Sn49NAnC:
{"id":"Sn49NAnC","lastModified":"2016-05-07T08:12:16.144Z","names":["Clarified Butter","Ghee"],"description":"Ghee is very commonly used in Indian cuisine. Buy from Indian grocery stores or make your own. 

Heat pure, unsalted butter till it melts completely. Continue heating, you will first see some foaming on top and eventually a browning residue at the bottom of the pan. Strain off and discard the residue and what you are left with is ghee. 

You don't have to refrigerate ghee, although it makes no difference if you do. ","category":"Dairy, Eggs and Non-dairy Cheeses","vegan":false}

ingredient:item.c0STLmcq:
{"id":"c0STLmcq","lastModified":"2016-05-07T08:12:30.322Z","names":["Elaichi","Green Cardamom"],"description":"Refers to whole cardamom pods containing the seeds. They are generally used whole to flavour curries and rice dishes. The pods are discarded once the dish is done. 

You can also use ground cardamom seeds, available in stores as ground cardamom. It is best to make your own though, as it is simply a matter of peeling off the skin of the pod and crushing the seeds. 

Buy from local Indian or Middle-Eastern grocery stores and store in airtight containers in a cool place. ","category":"Herbs and Spices","vegan":true}

ingredient:item.bsSuyXu6:
{"id":"bsSuyXu6","lastModified":"2016-05-07T08:14:23.579Z","names":["Long White Potato","Potato"],"description":"A very versatile and popular vegetable, potatoes can be boiled, roasted, steamed, roasted, baked, fried or used to thicken and add bulk to soups, stews and curries. They can be used peeled or unpeeled. 

Several varieties are available - baby potatoes, finger potatoes, purple or red potatoes and so on. In most recipes, use a generic version unless otherwise specified.

Store them in the pantry in a cool, dark and dry place and they will last for at least a month. Don't refrigerate","category":"Vegetables and Fruits","vegan":true}

ingredient:item.1Af_VldR:
{"id":"1Af_VldR","lastModified":"2016-05-07T08:15:53.777Z","names":["Asam Jawa","Indian Date","Tamarind"],"description":"Refers to the pulp extracted from the tamarind pod. It is used as a souring agent in several cuisines. 

Avoid buying ready to use tamarind paste or juice sold in supermarkets. Cheaper, longer-lasting and much more flavourful bricks of the pulp are sold in Indian grocery stores. Soak small amount of the pulp in warm water and squeeze out the juice whenever needed. Store tamarind in an airtight container in the pantry in a cool, dark place. It will last for several months, even a year. 

Measurements in the recipes are given in grams of pulp that will need to be soaked.","category":"Vegetables and Fruits","vegan":true}
